Your diagnostics are the compass we needed. The laptop’s limits are now pretty clear:

BGE-large embeddings: about 2 texts/sec on CPU
Cross-encoder: about 23.7 pairs/sec
FAISS: excellent, about 1,292 queries/sec
Sparse SGD: fast

So the laptop can run a strong model, but it cannot afford unlimited model search, duplicate processes, full Optuna, and heavy logreg_saga_balanced cross-validation all at once. The bottleneck is not FAISS anymore. The bottleneck is CPU-only transformer embedding when the cache misses and large supervised CV candidates, especially logistic regression and boosted models on a 62k × 80k sparse matrix.

I created a laptop-tuned version of the autocoder that adds one important control:

--candidate_models

That lets us decide exactly which supervised model families are allowed, instead of letting the script run a huge tournament that may take days.

